benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog/priceList - Retrieve priceList for a given subscription and date

covered: Valid requests: TC01-TC04, TC16, TC18 and TC21 exercise successful retrievals for combinations of subscriptionId/requestedDate, large-volume subscriptions, backward compatibility, and date-boundary correctness; content-type and basic PriceList JSON checks are included.

Query-parameter permutations and validation: TC01-TC07, TC11, TC12 and TC19 cover presence/absence of parameters, malformed values, oversized values, extra/unexpected parameters and partial/malformed inputs.
Authorization & basic security: TC08 covers missing/invalid auth (401). Injection and XSS attack vectors are covered (TC10, TC22) and include checks that internal details are not exposed.

Error handling & dependencies: TC06 (non-existent subscription -> 404), TC13 (empty DB -> 404/empty), TC09 (service down -> 503), TC20 (dependent service failure -> 502) and TC17 (retry after transient failures) exercise dependency and error pathways.
Performance: TC14, TC15 and TC18 address response-time expectations under normal, peak and large-data conditions.
Regression & edge cases: TC21 covers date-boundary regression behavior; TC05/TC07 address invalid parameter formats; TC03/TC04/TC13 cover behavior when parameters are omitted or DB is empty.
gaps: Pagination: No tests for pagination or behavior when the API returns collections/history (if the endpoint supports paging).
Caching behavior: No tests for cache-related headers (ETag, Cache-Control), conditional GETs (If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since) or 304 Not Modified responses.
Rate limiting/throttling: No tests simulate request bursts to verify 429 Too Many Requests and Retry-After handling.
Authorization scope/permissions: Tests cover missing/invalid tokens (401) but not authenticated-but-unauthorized scenarios (403), expired tokens, or scope-based access control.

Schema/contract validation: 'valid PriceList JSON object' is asserted generically but there are no explicit JSON schema or field-level assertions (required fields, types, currency/amount correctness).
Server error sanitation: No explicit test for 500 Internal Server Error to verify sanitized error messages and no stack-trace/internal info leakage.
Content negotiation: No tests for Accept header variations or 406 Not Acceptable behavior.
Ambiguous acceptance expectations: Several scenarios allow "200 or default" or "404 or empty" — tests do not assert a single deterministic behavior per the specification.
Date edge-case coverage: Leap days, timezone/normalization issues and additional date-format edge cases are not explicitly tested.
recommendations: Add explicit JSON-schema/contract tests for the PriceList response (verify required fields, data types, price amounts, currency, planId, effective date semantics).
Clarify API contract for omitted parameters (define whether endpoint should return a default PriceList or an error) and update TC03/TC04/TC13 to assert the exact expected behavior.
If the endpoint can return collections/history, add pagination tests (page size, offsets/markers, boundary cases); if not, add an explicit test asserting pagination is not applicable.
Add caching tests: verify ETag and Cache-Control headers, perform conditional GETs (If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since) and assert 304 responses when appropriate.
Add rate-limiting/throttling tests that simulate bursts to assert 429 responses and correct Retry-After headers; also test behavior under sustained high load.
Extend authorization tests to include 403 Forbidden (authenticated but unauthorized), expired tokens, and token-scope permutations.
Add a test to simulate a 500 Internal Server Error (e.g., DB exception) to verify sanitized error responses and no internal stack traces are returned to clients.
Add content-negotiation tests for Accept header variations and 406 handling where applicable.
Expand date-related tests to include leap years, end-of-day boundaries, and any timezone/normalization edge cases relevant to requestedDate handling.

Turn ambiguous "or" expectations into deterministic acceptance criteria, and map each Gherkin scenario to a single expected HTTP status/body so tests can be asserted reliably and used in automated CI checks.
